00:49:43,013 --> 00:49:45,447
It's like, "Okay, that grows."

965
00:49:45,549 --> 00:49:49,417
It's not like it's okay, but
you're not gonna be hooked.

966
00:49:49,519 --> 00:49:50,611
But people that are
on painkillers,

967
00:49:50,721 --> 00:49:51,813
they're hooked, you know?

968
00:49:51,922 --> 00:49:53,014
It gets you by <i>the...</i>

969
00:49:53,123 --> 00:49:56,786
and it's just, from that point
on, you're screwed, you know?

970
00:49:56,893 --> 00:49:59,555
You have to have it,
and you basically will lose...

971
00:49:59,663 --> 00:50:00,857
I've seen people
just lose themselves.

972
00:50:00,998 --> 00:50:02,693
You know someone, a good friend,

973
00:50:02,799 --> 00:50:05,131
you know, and they're the person
you know,

974
00:50:05,235 --> 00:50:08,136
and then down the path,
they've used so much

975
00:50:08,238 --> 00:50:09,762
that they'll flip on you

976
00:50:09,873 --> 00:50:11,602
and do whatever they can
to get their next fix.

977
00:50:11,708 --> 00:50:13,539
They'll just lose their soul
almost.

978
00:50:15,579 --> 00:50:19,447
It was not anything
you'd ever wish on anybody...

979
00:50:19,549 --> 00:50:21,779
to lose a child.

980
00:50:22,285 --> 00:50:26,688
Blake was a very outgoing kid

981
00:50:26,790 --> 00:50:28,781
as, you know, in elementary,
junior high.

982
00:50:28,892 --> 00:50:30,519
Very popular.
Had a lot of friends.

983
00:50:30,627 --> 00:50:32,151
He was always kind of the leader
of the group.

984
00:50:32,262 --> 00:50:33,923
He was doing well, you know,

985
00:50:34,064 --> 00:50:36,532
until he hit about his sophomore
year in high school.

986
00:50:36,633 --> 00:50:39,101
Got kicked off the team
as a sophomore,

987
00:50:39,202 --> 00:50:42,831
grades started to drop,
and his personality changed.

988
00:50:42,939 --> 00:50:44,930
He just became reclusive.

989
00:50:45,042 --> 00:50:47,772
He'd come home,
and he'd go to sleep.

990
00:50:47,878 --> 00:50:50,039
We never thought
anything about it.

991
00:50:50,147 --> 00:50:53,810
Then we started questioning him,
and we started looking at him,

992
00:50:53,917 --> 00:50:55,282
and once you look at him,
then you can see it.

993
00:50:55,385 --> 00:50:56,682
You can see the signs.

994
00:50:56,787 --> 00:50:58,721
You know, he'd come home,
and his eyes would be bloodshot.

995
00:50:58,822 --> 00:51:01,689
He'd be tired.
He was pale.

996
00:51:01,792 --> 00:51:04,522
There was many times
where I had to jump in

997
00:51:04,628 --> 00:51:06,186
between my husband and Blake

998
00:51:06,296 --> 00:51:08,662
because he was so frustrated
with him.

999
00:51:08,765 --> 00:51:12,098
Blake would be high
or would have drugs on him.

1000
00:51:12,202 --> 00:51:14,193
My youngest daughter,
who was in junior high,

1001
00:51:14,304 --> 00:51:16,499
would come home
and go straight upstairs.

1002
00:51:16,606 --> 00:51:17,971
My other son was serving
a mission,

1003
00:51:18,075 --> 00:51:20,066
so he was kind of
out of the loop anyway.

1004
00:51:20,177 --> 00:51:22,543
And we all knew that eventually
he was gonna overdose

1005
00:51:22,646 --> 00:51:23,738
doing what he'd done.

1006
00:51:23,847 --> 00:51:24,939
We knew that he couldn't do
what he was doing

1007
00:51:25,048 --> 00:51:26,140
and live through it.

1008
00:51:26,249 --> 00:51:30,015
And I was upstairs
getting ready to go to work,

1009
00:51:30,120 --> 00:51:32,816
and my husband came running
upstairs and screaming at me,

1010
00:51:32,923 --> 00:51:36,017
saying, "Suzanne, come down.
Something's wrong with Blake."

1011
00:51:36,126 --> 00:51:37,821
And he was laying on the bed,

1012
00:51:37,928 --> 00:51:40,123
and my first thought was that
he had cotton in his nose

1013
00:51:40,263 --> 00:51:42,754
'cause he had foam coming
out of his nose and his mouth,

1014
00:51:42,866 --> 00:51:46,199
and then I realized
that it was mucous

1015
00:51:46,303 --> 00:51:48,271
and that he most likely
had a seizure.

1016
00:51:48,371 --> 00:51:50,896
I pulled him off the bed
and couldn't get his mouth open

1017
00:51:51,007 --> 00:51:52,599
'cause I think he was still
having a seizure,

1018
00:51:52,709 --> 00:51:54,700
and I remember thinking
as I was prying his mouth open

1019
00:51:54,811 --> 00:51:56,073
that he was gonna
bite my finger off,

1020
00:51:56,179 --> 00:51:57,703
but you don't care, you know.

1021
00:51:57,814 --> 00:52:02,615
And I got his mouth open
and started doing CPR on him.

1022
00:52:04,621 --> 00:52:06,054
It was probably
the hardest thing

1023
00:52:06,156 --> 00:52:08,283
I've ever had to do
in my life...

1024
00:52:08,391 --> 00:52:09,722
to sit there and look at my son,

1025
00:52:09,826 --> 00:52:12,294
who had a gazillion tubes
going into him.

1026
00:52:12,395 --> 00:52:14,226
You know, at that point,
he wasn't a person.

1027
00:52:14,331 --> 00:52:16,697
He was just somebody
that they were trying to save.

1028
00:52:16,800 --> 00:52:21,601
And I remember thinking
that it's almost okay,

1029
00:52:21,705 --> 00:52:23,036
that he'll be better off,

1030
00:52:23,140 --> 00:52:26,132
that he's been through so much
hell in the last two years

1031
00:52:26,243 --> 00:52:30,270
that maybe this is
a better thing for him.

1032
00:52:30,380 --> 00:52:34,316
The physician told us
at that point that he would die,

1033
00:52:34,417 --> 00:52:36,180
that we would be taking him
off the ventilator

1034
00:52:36,286 --> 00:52:37,719
later on that afternoon,

1035
00:52:37,821 --> 00:52:38,947
so to get our family together

1036
00:52:39,055 --> 00:52:41,182
and to get everybody there
to say their last...

1037
00:52:41,291 --> 00:52:42,918
you know, say their goodbyes
to Blake.

1038
00:52:43,026 --> 00:52:45,654
And it was horrible.

1039
00:52:45,762 --> 00:52:47,286
I mean, I remember standing
against the wall,

1040
00:52:47,397 --> 00:52:48,728
sliding down it, sobbing,

1041
00:52:48,832 --> 00:52:49,924
and my daughter was sobbing

1042
00:52:50,033 --> 00:52:52,399
and my other daughter was
and my husband,

1043
00:52:52,502 --> 00:52:55,630
and grandmas and grandpas
and friends.

1044
00:52:55,739 --> 00:52:58,139
I mean, all the friends
from Bonneville High.

1045
00:52:58,241 --> 00:53:01,870
They had to call security
to clear the halls

1046
00:53:01,978 --> 00:53:05,072
because there were so many kids
that were standing there crying.

1047
00:53:08,718 --> 00:53:12,814
I woke up in the hospital
about five days later,

1048
00:53:12,923 --> 00:53:14,686
four or five days later,

1049
00:53:14,791 --> 00:53:17,817
and I was in the hospital
altogether for about nine days.

1050
00:53:17,928 --> 00:53:20,192
They told my parents
that I would...

1051
00:53:20,297 --> 00:53:23,630
prepare to take me
off life support,

1052
00:53:23,767 --> 00:53:27,726
and I just decided that's...
that's not my life.

1053
00:53:27,837 --> 00:53:29,634
You only get one life,

1054
00:53:29,739 --> 00:53:33,641
and that's not the life
I wanted to live.

1055
00:53:33,743 --> 00:53:35,005
You know,
everything's good again.

1056
00:53:35,111 --> 00:53:36,203
It's hard.

1057
00:53:36,313 --> 00:53:38,941
Like Blake said, he takes it
a day at a time, and so do we.

1058
00:53:39,049 --> 00:53:41,244
You know, every morning I get
up, I go in and look at him,

1059
00:53:41,351 --> 00:53:43,410
make sure he's still breathing.

1060
00:53:43,520 --> 00:53:44,817
And I probably will do that

1061
00:53:44,921 --> 00:53:48,357
until he, you know,
moves out, anyway.

1062
00:53:48,458 --> 00:53:52,792
But it's... You know, it
consumes your life even after.

1063
00:53:52,896 --> 00:53:55,456
Even now that he's clean,
it still consumes my life.

1064
00:53:55,565 --> 00:53:57,157
The drug problem has gone

1065
00:53:57,300 --> 00:54:00,030
through the Terrace in Ogden
like a disease,

1066
00:54:00,136 --> 00:54:03,799
wiping friends out,
my buddies out one by one.

1067
00:54:03,907 --> 00:54:06,740
I mean, it's...
it's overwhelming.

1068
00:54:07,978 --> 00:54:12,745
My perspective on it was,
I mean, it's only a pill.

1069
00:54:14,284 --> 00:54:17,776
I mean, it's only one pill,
you know, once a day, if that.

1070
00:54:17,887 --> 00:54:20,151
The teenagers would get
their drugs by...

1071
00:54:20,257 --> 00:54:22,748
I mean, there was people
on the streets...

1072
00:54:22,859 --> 00:54:25,123
old ladies that would get
prescribed it.

1073
00:54:25,228 --> 00:54:29,426
There was people
that had back pains.

1074
00:54:29,532 --> 00:54:31,727
I mean, the one day of the month

1075
00:54:31,835 --> 00:54:32,927
where they got
their prescription filled,

1076
00:54:33,036 --> 00:54:36,233
there'd be four or five people
at her front door.

1077
00:54:36,339 --> 00:54:38,864
My whole sophomore year,
I don't think I experimented

1078
00:54:38,975 --> 00:54:42,968
with anything more
than Lortab or Percocet,

1079
00:54:43,079 --> 00:54:45,070
and my junior year

1080
00:54:45,181 --> 00:54:47,911
is when I started to bump it up
a little bit.

1081
00:54:48,018 --> 00:54:51,112
I would start, I mean, doing
OxyContin, morphine suckers,

1082
00:54:51,221 --> 00:54:54,987
and my senior year
just got out of control.

1083
00:54:55,091 --> 00:54:59,084
I mean, I was all over
the place looking for it,

1084
00:54:59,195 --> 00:55:01,720
doing two or three, four,
five pills a day.

1085
00:55:01,831 --> 00:55:05,096
I mean, spending hundreds
of dollars a day doing it.

1086
00:55:05,201 --> 00:55:07,692
Well, when I was in high school,
I would look at heroin

1087
00:55:07,804 --> 00:55:11,831
as in a whole different game
than OxyContin.

1088
00:55:11,941 --> 00:55:13,704
I mean,
I've never even seen heroin

1089
00:55:13,810 --> 00:55:17,143
for the fact
that just the name "heroin."

1090
00:55:17,247 --> 00:55:21,274
But it's in the same ballpark.

1091
00:55:22,319 --> 00:55:26,847
It kills people
just the same way heroin does.

1092
00:55:27,490 --> 00:55:30,459
OxyContin is actually
a synthetic-based heroin.

1093
00:55:30,560 --> 00:55:33,757
It's heroin into a pill.

1094
00:55:33,863 --> 00:55:35,262
While working undercover,

1095
00:55:35,365 --> 00:55:41,998
I found myself almost
in a sociological project,

1096
00:55:42,105 --> 00:55:47,168
trying to figure out "What
is making this so enjoyable?

1097
00:55:47,277 --> 00:55:52,078
Why are they just jumping
to get in to try this stuff?"

1098
00:55:52,182 --> 00:55:55,777
And we got into conversation
of...

1099
00:55:55,885 --> 00:55:58,012
One Sunday evening,
we were at a party.

1100
00:55:58,121 --> 00:56:02,080
I was surrounded
by a bunch of teenagers.

1101
00:56:02,192 --> 00:56:04,786
We got on the conversation
of religion.

1102
00:56:04,894 --> 00:56:05,986
Come to find out,

1103
00:56:06,096 --> 00:56:08,997
the overwhelming majority
of the kids around me were LDS.

1104
00:56:09,099 --> 00:56:10,828
And so I asked them,
"Well, don't you feel guilty

1105
00:56:10,934 --> 00:56:12,799
about going to church tomorrow?"

1106
00:56:12,902 --> 00:56:14,893
And they said,
"Well, yeah, but you know what?

1107
00:56:15,004 --> 00:56:16,938
It's really not
against the Word of Wisdom."

1108
00:56:17,040 --> 00:56:18,905
And I said, "Oh, yeah?
Well, how so?"

1109
00:56:19,008 --> 00:56:21,772
"Well, it's a pill.
It's not that big of a deal.

1110
00:56:21,878 --> 00:56:23,345
It makes me feel good.
So what?

1111
00:56:23,446 --> 00:56:25,539
It's not alcohol.
I'm not smoking anything.

1112
00:56:25,648 --> 00:56:27,309
I'm not sticking anything
in my arm.

1113
00:56:27,417 --> 00:56:30,250
I'm just taking a pill
and drinking some water.

1114
00:56:30,353 --> 00:56:31,911
Big deal."

1115
00:56:32,021 --> 00:56:33,249
There are a lot of parents

1116
00:56:33,356 --> 00:56:36,917
that just have no idea what's
going on with their children,

1117
00:56:37,026 --> 00:56:40,325
and it's not because they're
not paying attention maybe,

1118
00:56:40,397 --> 00:56:44,458
but sometimes it's just that
you got to dig a little deeper.

1119
00:56:44,567 --> 00:56:46,000
We had no clue.

1120
00:56:46,102 --> 00:56:48,093
Really very good at hiding it.

1121
00:56:48,204 --> 00:56:53,164
I mean, it's not like we're
not a pretty close family.

1122
00:56:53,276 --> 00:56:58,373
A young lady, recently married,
had forged a prescription.

1123
00:56:58,481 --> 00:57:00,381
She was involved
in a car accident,

1124
00:57:00,483 --> 00:57:06,115
and she was legally prescribed
Lortab and hydrocodone.

1125
00:57:06,222 --> 00:57:10,454
She found herself addicted
within a short period of time

1126
00:57:10,560 --> 00:57:12,027
to the Lortab and hydrocodone.

1127
00:57:12,128 --> 00:57:13,220
So, she was altering...

1128
00:57:13,329 --> 00:57:16,492
She was going to different
doctors and doctor shopping,

1129
00:57:16,599 --> 00:57:18,999
receiving a prescription,

1130
00:57:19,102 --> 00:57:20,535
but then she was altering
the prescription

1131
00:57:20,637 --> 00:57:22,434
to get her more pills.

1132
00:57:22,539 --> 00:57:25,406
The pharmacist caught on
to this, turned her in.

1133
00:57:25,508 --> 00:57:28,568
I conducted my investigation
and called the house.

1134
00:57:28,678 --> 00:57:29,975
I spoke to her husband.

1135
00:57:30,079 --> 00:57:31,171
Come to find out,

1136
00:57:31,281 --> 00:57:35,217
she was a very key member
of the Relief Society,

1137
00:57:35,318 --> 00:57:39,152
and he was afraid
at how this was gonna be viewed

1138
00:57:39,255 --> 00:57:41,621
within his religious culture.

1139
00:57:41,724 --> 00:57:43,021
But I could give you a list

1140
00:57:43,126 --> 00:57:45,856
of so many people
that shop doctors,

1141
00:57:45,962 --> 00:57:47,987
that are at the pharmacy
late at night

1142
00:57:48,097 --> 00:57:50,622
or even at emergency rooms
coming up with something

1143
00:57:50,733 --> 00:57:52,428
because they ran out of drugs.

1144
00:57:52,535 --> 00:57:53,968
And you would look
at some of these people,

1145
00:57:54,037 --> 00:57:55,629
go, "Are you kidding me?

1146
00:57:55,738 --> 00:57:58,673
This guys takes them, but isn't
he so-and-so in the community?"

1147
00:57:58,775 --> 00:58:00,003
It's ridiculous.

1148
00:58:00,109 --> 00:58:01,201
That's why so many people
are hiding it.

1149
00:58:01,311 --> 00:58:02,903
That's why everybody goes
through this denial

1150
00:58:03,012 --> 00:58:04,104
and hiding it every day

1151
00:58:04,214 --> 00:58:05,408
because they don't
want it to affect

1152
00:58:05,515 --> 00:58:07,244
what happens in their church

1153
00:58:07,350 --> 00:58:09,045
or their standing
in their church

1154
00:58:09,152 --> 00:58:10,483
or their standing
in the community or whatever.

1155
00:58:10,587 --> 00:58:11,884
We can't let it affect that,

1156
00:58:11,988 --> 00:58:16,118
so we hide in this gray area
in the middle here of denial

1157
00:58:16,226 --> 00:58:17,853
and, you know.

1158
00:58:17,961 --> 00:58:19,428
"Well, you know,
but he's got a bad back,

1159
00:58:19,529 --> 00:58:20,655
and that's why he takes it,"

1160
00:58:20,763 --> 00:58:23,027
or "He's sick because..."
And you know what?

1161
00:58:23,132 --> 00:58:25,930
And it's just because nobody
wants to take responsibility

1162
00:58:26,035 --> 00:58:27,093
for where they're at.

1163
00:58:27,203 --> 00:58:28,465
Nobody wants to really fess up

1164
00:58:28,571 --> 00:58:30,334
and say that I got a problem,
that I am sick,

1165
00:58:30,440 --> 00:58:32,533
and it's not just a bad back
or a bad shoulder,

1166
00:58:32,642 --> 00:58:34,337
and that I need help.

1167
00:58:34,444 --> 00:58:36,036
The reality of it is,

1168
00:58:36,145 --> 00:58:38,909
is that people
do not want to acknowledge

1169
00:58:39,015 --> 00:58:42,314
that which is uncomfortable
for them to see.

1170
00:58:53,496 --> 00:58:57,557
During my childhood, we were
a very, very LDS family,

1171
00:58:57,667 --> 00:58:59,430
and we'd always go to church.

1172
00:58:59,536 --> 00:59:02,096
We'd always go to
my grandma's house on Sundays

1173
00:59:02,205 --> 00:59:03,638
and have Sunday dinner,

1174
00:59:03,740 --> 00:59:07,972
and we just had a happy family.

1175
00:59:08,077 --> 00:59:11,103
I thought that Macall,
when she was in gymnastics,

1176
00:59:11,214 --> 00:59:13,045
that she was gonna go
all the way.

1177
00:59:13,149 --> 00:59:15,583
She was going to become
an Olympian.

1178
00:59:15,685 --> 00:59:19,485
She was going to just
blow us all away.

1179
00:59:19,589 --> 00:59:22,183
I was on floor
and I was doing a tumbling pass

1180
00:59:22,292 --> 00:59:23,384
and I landed short

1181
00:59:23,493 --> 00:59:26,189
and I hyperextended my knee
and tore my ACL

1182
00:59:26,296 --> 00:59:28,025
and I had to have surgery.

1183
00:59:28,131 --> 00:59:29,462
It took a year to heal

1184
00:59:29,566 --> 00:59:31,534
and I tried to go
back to gymnastics,

1185
00:59:31,634 --> 00:59:33,192
but it was too painful.

1186
00:59:33,303 --> 00:59:34,531
It was <i>so...</i>

1187
00:59:34,637 --> 00:59:37,071
Everything just wasn't right.

1188
00:59:37,173 --> 00:59:38,697
I just couldn't get
back into it.

1189
00:59:38,808 --> 00:59:40,742
I remember Macall wanted to go
to school, though.

1190
00:59:40,843 --> 00:59:42,504
She would do gymnastics, too.

1191
00:59:42,612 --> 00:59:44,307
She wanted to go to gymnastics,

1192
00:59:44,414 --> 00:59:46,211
and I just
didn't want to take her.

1193
00:59:46,316 --> 00:59:48,375
I started slacking
on being a mom,

1194
00:59:48,484 --> 00:59:50,349
and, you know, she was like,

1195
00:59:50,453 --> 00:59:52,421
"Please, Mom.
Take me to gymnastics.

1196
00:59:52,522 --> 00:59:54,490
Please, please."
And I was like, "Ugh."

1197
00:59:54,591 --> 00:59:58,425
I mean, it was one exit away.
You know, it was nothing.

1198
00:59:58,528 --> 01:00:00,689
So I just ended up just staying
into school

1199
01:00:00,797 --> 01:00:04,198
and getting a social life
and going with my friends.

1200
01:00:04,334 --> 01:00:06,802
And then my parents got divorced

1201
01:00:06,903 --> 01:00:10,669
and I was living with my mother
and my sister Lindsy,

